NEW YORK-Roy Wilkins, exc
cutive secretary of the National
Association for the Advancement
of Colored People, indicated Ne
groes may play politics at the
polls in November if the civil
rights legislation stalled.


At the annual NAACP meet
ing wilkins said. Although
President Johnson has given the
civil rights bill top priority there
is every indication that the House
rules committee under Chairman
Howard Smith of Virginia, may
not finish action on this bill seven
full months after 1t was sub
mitted."


He further announced that Ne
groes may be forced to re-
examine their support of the
Democratic party of which Mr..
Smith is an ornament.

RACE TO USE FORCE
AT THE POLLS SOON

Mrs. Ruth O Neil was chosen as
chairman of the Maricopa c ounty
Board of Supervisors on Jan. E.
She succeeds Barney Burns. 1t
is her third term as chairman.


She became the first woman
supervisor in Arizona in 1859
when she vas appointed to COM
plete the unexpired term of her
husband who died.


AS District 8 supervisor she
represents the entire western
section of the county, from Cen
trail Avenue east and including
Glendale, Peoria, Avondale,
Buckeye, Tolleson, Wickenburg
and ella Bend.

AUBURN, Alabama Harold
Franklin of Montgomery, the first
Negro student at Auburn Univer-
sity, attended his first classes
without incident Monday.


A small group of state troop
ers we're on hand to assist city
and college police. but federal
agents, who had been barred from
campus by Gov. George Wallace,
watched nearby.


Franklin, 81 yr. old graduate
student is working towards mas
ter's degree in history and po-
litical science. He is living in
a men dormitory and hasn't
experienced any hostilities.

ST. JOSEPH, Mo. = Voters in
this city have approved a city
ordinance prohibiting racial dis
elimination in some places of
public accommodations.


They favored the lowering of
racial bars in hotels, motels,
restaurants, and places of enter
tainment by narrow margin
5,O3l votes to 4, 1872.


But the measure, strongly sup
ported by Mayor Arthur ]. Meers,
ministerial groups, and the
press, does not affect private
clubs, beer halls and taverns.

OK'D IN MISSOURI

The engagement of Miss Kay
Francis Wilson and 1t. Isaac
Sanders Payne has been an
nounced. The marriage is set in
March.


Miss Wilson Is the daughter of
Mr.. and Mrs. Charles w. Wilson
Amarillo, Texas.


Her fiance's parents are Mr..
and Mrs. Isaac Payne, Portland,
Ore.


She is graduate of Arizona
State University where she mai
ored in business administration.
She is a member of the Alpha
Kappa Alpha sorority.


Ly. Payne, a U. S. Air Force
Academy graduate, Is enrolled
in pilot training at Williams Air
Force Base. He Is a member
of the Kappa Alpha Pts frater-
nifty.

Senator Barry Coldwater, SIS
yr. old Republican from Arizona,
announced last Friday thathe was
a candidate for his party s nomi-
nation for the president.


His announcement came after
he had conferred with Republican
state party leaders and several
friends and his family.


The announcement was carried
over television and radio by rep
resentatives of national and local
communication media.


The Arizona senator said he
had been asked by hundreds of
persons since the last convention
to run for the office. He said he
had taken considerable time be-
fore making his decision.


He said, Zone of the great
attributes of our American two
party system has always been
the reflected differences In prin-
ciple. AS a general rule, one party
has emphasized individual liberty
and the other has favored the
extension of government power.
l am convinced that today a ma
iority in the Republican Party
believes in the essential empha-
sis on individual liberty.


IL have been spelling our my
position now for 10 years in the
Senate and for years before that
here in my own state. l will
spell it out even further in the
months to come. | was once
asked what kind of Republican
l was. l replied that | was not
a 'me-too' Republican. That still
holds. will not change my be-
liefs to win votes. | will offer
a choice, not an echo.


"This will not be an engage
ment of personalities. 1t will be
an engagement of principles"

DALLAS, Texas = The state
wide voter registration drive for
100000 was opened Dec. 80 by
the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.


NAACP representative VIC.
Patton, helped organize and plan
the campaign. He said people
from all Texas branches, and
areas where there are no branch
es, are engaged in the drive.
Most efforts, however, are being
concentrated in East Texas, he
added.


NAACP branches are seeking
to have poll tax collectors depu-
tized in every county where a
branch is located. In Texas, pay
ment of the poll tax qualities
citizen to vote. The last day for
poll tax payment is January 81.


Sunday, January IL, has been
designated as "Poll Tax Empha-
sis Day." Ministers and all or
CARNATIONS have been urged to
boserve this day.

the Cleveland Browns, who set
new all-time rushing records,
was awarded the Jim Thorpe
Trophy as the outstanding ma
tional Football League player of
the year. Also sharing the award
will be Y. "A. Title, the New York
Giants great quarterback.

MONROVIA, Liberia = Pres
ident William Tubman, 6S yr. old
head executive of Africa's old
est republic begins his sixth four
year term.


Liberia was founded by the
American Colonization Society
with freed slaves from the United
States in 1922. Nearly 10000
freedmen we're shipped to Ii

lation today of almost one mil
lion.


Tubman became president In
1914. He is responsible for much
of the progress in the small
poor nation.
